	only as of the date made, and advise readers that various factors, including those described above, could affect our financial performance and could cause our actual results or circumstances for future periods to differ materially from those
	anticipated or projected.&nbsp;See also Item 1A, Risk Factors, of this Annual Report on Form 10-K for further information.&nbsp;Except as required by law, we do not undertake, and specifically disclaim any obligation to publicly release any
	revisions to any forward-looking statements to reflect the occurrence of anticipated or unanticipated events or circumstances after the date of such statements.
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:22PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">

</P>
<P STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:1.0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:2PT;BORDER-BOTTOM:1.00PT SOLID #000000">
	&nbsp;

<EFX_BUSINESS>
<A NAME="FIS_BUSINESS"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<A NAME="D120623D10K_HTM_TOC120623_2">
</A>
	ITEM
	1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;BUSINESS
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:1.0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:2PT;BORDER-BOTTOM:1.00PT SOLID #000000">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:18PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	GENERAL
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Financial Institutions, Inc.,
	(the &#147;Company&#148;) is a financial holding company organized in 1931 under the laws of New York State (&#147;New York&#148; or &#147;NYS&#148;). The principal office of the Company is located at 220 Liberty Street, Warsaw, New York 14569 and
	its telephone number is (585) 786-1100. The Company was incorporated on September&nbsp;15, 1931, but the continuity of its banking business is traced to the organization of the National Bank of Geneva on March&nbsp;28, 1817.&nbsp;Except as the
	context otherwise requires, the Company and its direct and indirect subsidiaries are collectively referred to in this report as the &#147;Company.&#148;&nbsp;Five Star Bank is referred to as Five Star Bank, &#147;FSB&#148; or &#147;the Bank,&#148;
	and Scott Danahy Naylon, LLC is referred to as &#147;SDN.&#148; The consolidated financial statements include the accounts of the Company, the Bank and SDN. The Company&#146;s common stock is traded on the NASDAQ Global Select Market under the
	ticker symbol &#147;FISI.&#148;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	At December&nbsp;31, 2015, the Company had consolidated total assets of $3.38 billion, deposits of $2.73
	billion and shareholders&#146; equity of $293.8 million.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The Company&#146;s primary business is the operation of its subsidiaries.&nbsp;It
	does not engage in any other substantial business activities.&nbsp;At December&nbsp;31, 2015, the Company had two direct wholly-owned subsidiaries: (1) the Bank, which provides a full range of banking services to consumer, commercial and municipal
	customers in Western and Central New York; and (2) SDN, which sells various premium-based insurance policies on a commission basis to commercial and consumer customers.&nbsp;At December&nbsp;31, 2015, the Bank represented 99.3% and SDN represented
	0.6% of the consolidated assets of the Company.&nbsp;Further discussion of our segments is included in Note 20 to the Company&#146;s Consolidated Financial Statements included under Item 8 of this Annual Report on Form 10-K.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:14PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Five Star Bank
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The Bank is a New York
	chartered bank that has its headquarters at 55 North Main Street, Warsaw, NY, and a total of 50 full-service banking offices in the New York State counties of Allegany, Cattaraugus, Cayuga, Chautauqua, Chemung, Erie, Genesee, Livingston, Monroe,
	Ontario, Orleans, Seneca, Steuben, Wyoming and Yates counties.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	At December&nbsp;31, 2015, the Bank had total assets of $3.36 billion,
	investment securities of $1.03 billion, net loans of $2.06 billion, deposits of $2.74 billion and shareholders&#146; equity of $302.6 million, compared to total assets of $3.07 billion, investment securities of $916.9 million, net loans of $1.88
	billion, deposits of $2.46 billion and shareholders&#146; equity of $256.3 million at December&nbsp;31, 2014. The Bank offers deposit products, which include checking and NOW accounts, savings accounts, and certificates of deposit, as its principal
	source of funding.&nbsp;The Bank&#146;s deposits are insured up to the maximum permitted by the Bank Insurance Fund (the &#147;Insurance Fund&#148;) of the Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation (&#147;FDIC&#148;).&nbsp;The Bank offers a variety of
	loan products to its customers, including commercial and consumer loans and commercial and residential mortgage loans.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:14PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Scott Danahy Naylon,
	LLC
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Acquired in August&nbsp;2014, SDN is a full-service insurance agency founded in 1923 and headquartered in Amherst, NY.&nbsp;SDN
	offers personal, commercial and financial services products and serves over 6,000 clients in 44 states.&nbsp;For the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, SDN had total revenue of $5.0 million.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	SDN&#146;s primary market area is Erie and Niagara counties in New York State.&nbsp;Most lines of personal insurance are provided, including
	automobile, homeowners, boat, recreational vehicle, landlord, and umbrella coverage.&nbsp;Commercial insurance products are also provided, consisting of property, liability, automobile, inland marine, workers compensation, bonds, crop and umbrella
	insurance.&nbsp;SDN also provides the following financial services products:&nbsp;life and disability insurance, Medicare supplements, long-term care, annuities, mutual funds, retirement programs and New York State disability.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:14PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Courier Capital
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Acquired in
	January&nbsp;2016, Courier Capital, LLC is an SEC-registered investment advisory and wealth management firm based in Western New York, with offices in Buffalo and Jamestown. With $1.2 billion in assets under management, Courier Capital offers
	customized investment management, investment consulting and retirement plan services to over 1,100 individuals, businesses and institutions.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	- 4 -
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage5"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D120623D10K_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Other Subsidiaries
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	In addition to the Bank and SDN, the Company had the following indirect wholly-owned subsidiary as of December&nbsp;31, 2015:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
<B>
	Five Star REIT, Inc.
</B>
<B>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;
</B>
	Five Star REIT, Inc., a wholly-owned subsidiary of the Bank, operates as a real estate investment
	trust that holds residential mortgages and commercial real estate loans.&nbsp;Five Star REIT provides additional flexibility and planning opportunities for the business of the Bank.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:14PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Business Strategy
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Our business strategy
	has been to maintain a community bank philosophy, which consists of focusing on and understanding the individualized banking and other financial services needs of individuals, municipalities and businesses of the local communities surrounding our
	primary service area. We believe this focus allows us to be more responsive to our customers&#146; needs and provide a high level of personal service that differentiates us from larger competitors, resulting in long-standing and broad-based banking
	relationships. Our core customers are primarily small- to medium-sized businesses, individuals and community organizations who prefer to build banking, insurance and wealth management relationships with a community bank that offers and combines high
	quality, competitively-priced products and services with personalized service. Because of our identity and origin as a locally operated bank, we believe that our level of personal service provides a competitive advantage over larger banks, which
	tend to consolidate decision-making authority outside local communities.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	A key aspect of our current business strategy is to foster a
	community-oriented culture where our customers and employees establish long-standing and mutually beneficial relationships. We believe that we are well-positioned to be a strong competitor within our market area because of our focus on community
	banking needs and customer service, our comprehensive suite of deposit, loan, insurance and&nbsp;wealth management products typically found at larger banks, our highly experienced management team and our strategically located banking
	centers.&nbsp;We believe that the foregoing factors all help to grow our core deposits, which supports a central element of our business strategy - the growth of a diversified and high-quality loan portfolio.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:14PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Acquisition Strategy
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	We will continue to
	explore market expansion opportunities in or near our current market areas as opportunities arise.&nbsp;Our primary focus will be on increasing market share within existing markets, while taking advantage of potential growth opportunities within our
	insurance and wealth management lines of business by acquiring new businesses that can be added to existing operations.&nbsp;We believe our capital position remains strong enough to support an active merger and acquisition strategy, and expansion of
	our core financial service businesses of banking, insurance and wealth management.&nbsp;Consequently, we continue to explore acquisition opportunities in these activities. In evaluating acquisition opportunities, we will balance the potential for
	earnings accretion with maintaining adequate capital levels, which could result in our common stock being the predominate form of consideration and/or the need for us to raise capital.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Conversations with potential strategic partners are occurring on a regular basis. The evaluation of any potential opportunity will favor a
	transaction that complements our core competencies and strategic intent, with a lesser emphasis being placed on geographic location or size.&nbsp;Additionally, we remain committed to maintaining a diversified revenue stream.&nbsp;Our senior
	management team has had extensive experience in acquisitions and post-acquisition integration of operations, and is prepared to act quickly should a potential opportunity arise, but will remain disciplined with its approach.&nbsp;We believe this
	experience positions us to successfully acquire and integrate additional financial services and banking businesses.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:14PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	MARKET AREAS AND COMPETITION
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	We provide a wide range of banking and financial services to individuals, municipalities and businesses through a network of over 50
	offices and an extensive ATM network throughout Western and Central New York.&nbsp;The region includes the counties of Allegany, Cattaraugus, Cayuga, Chautauqua, Chemung, Erie, Genesee, Livingston, Monroe, Ontario, Orleans, Schuyler, Seneca,
	Steuben, Wyoming and Yates counties.&nbsp;Our banking activities, though concentrated in the communities where we maintain branches, also extend into neighboring counties.&nbsp;In addition, we have expanded our consumer indirect lending presence to
	the Capital District of New York and Northern and Central Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Our market area is economically diversified in that we serve both
	rural markets and the larger markets in and around Rochester and Buffalo.&nbsp;Rochester and Buffalo are the two largest metropolitan areas in New York outside of New York City, with a combined population of over two million people.&nbsp;We
	anticipate continuing to increase our presence in and around these metropolitan statistical areas in the coming years.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	- 5 -
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage6"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D120623D10K_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	We face significant competition in both making loans and attracting deposits, as both Western and
	Central New York have a high density of financial institutions.&nbsp;Our competition for loans comes principally from commercial banks, savings banks, savings and loan associations, mortgage banking companies, credit unions, insurance companies and
	other financial service companies.&nbsp;Our most direct competition for deposits has historically come from commercial banks, savings banks and credit unions.&nbsp;We face additional competition for deposits from non-depository competitors such as
	the mutual fund industry, securities and brokerage firms and insurance companies.&nbsp;We generally compete with other financial service providers on factors such as level of customer service, responsiveness to customer needs, availability and
	pricing of products, and geographic location.&nbsp;Our industry frequently experiences merger activity, which affects competition by eliminating some institutions while potentially strengthening the franchises of others.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The following table presents the Bank&#146;s market share percentage for total deposits as of June&nbsp;30, 2015, in each county where we have
	operations. The table also indicates the ranking by deposit size in each market. All information in the table was obtained from SNL Financial of Charlottesville, Virginia, which compiles deposit data published by the FDIC as of June&nbsp;30, 2015
	and updates the information for any bank mergers and acquisitions completed subsequent to the reporting date.
</P>

<TD VALIGN="TOP" COLSPAN="15">
<P STYLE="LINE-HEIGHT:8.0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:2PT;BORDER-BOTTOM:1PX SOLID #000000;WIDTH:5%">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:1PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<SUP STYLE="FONT-SIZE:85%; VERTICAL-ALIGN:TOP">
	(1)
</SUP>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Number of branches current as of December&nbsp;31, 2015.
</P>

</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:14PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	INVESTMENT ACTIVITIES
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Our investment policy is contained within our overall Asset-Liability Management and Investment Policy. This policy dictates that investment
	decisions will be made based on the safety of the investment, liquidity requirements, potential returns, cash flow targets, need for collateral and desired risk parameters. In pursuing these objectives, we consider the ability of an investment to
	provide earnings consistent with factors related to quality, maturity, marketability, pledgeable nature and risk diversification. Our Treasurer, guided by our Asset-Liability Committee (&#147;ALCO&#148;), is responsible for investment portfolio
	decisions within the established policies.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Our investment securities strategy is focused on providing liquidity to meet loan demand and
	redeeming liabilities, meeting pledging requirements, managing credit risks, managing overall interest rate risks and maximizing portfolio yield.&nbsp;Our current policy generally limits security purchases to the following:
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT">
	U.S. treasury securities;
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:2PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT">
	U.S. government agency securities, which are securities issued by official Federal government bodies (e.g., the Government National Mortgage
	Association (&#147;GNMA&#148;) and the Small Business Administration (&#147;SBA&#148;)), and U.S. government-sponsored enterprise securities, which are securities issued by independent organizations that are in part sponsored by the federal
	government (e.g., the Federal Home Loan Bank (&#147;FHLB&#148;) system, the Federal National Mortgage Association (&#147;FNMA&#148;), the Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corporation (&#147;FHLMC&#148;) and the Federal Farm Credit Bureau);
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:2PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT">
	Mortgage-backed securities (&#147;MBS&#148;) include mortgage-backed pass-through securities, collateralized mortgage obligations and multi-family
	MBS issued by GNMA, FNMA and FHLMC;
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:2PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:2PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D120623D10K_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	LENDING ACTIVITIES
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	General
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	We offer a broad range of loans
	including commercial business and revolving lines of credit, commercial mortgages, equipment loans, residential mortgage loans and home equity loans and lines of credit, home improvement loans, automobile loans and personal loans.&nbsp;Newly
	originated and refinanced fixed rate residential mortgage loans are either retained in our portfolio or sold to the secondary market with servicing rights retained.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	We continually evaluate and update our lending policy.&nbsp;The key elements of our lending philosophy include the following:
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT">
	To ensure consistent underwriting, employees must share a common view of the risks inherent in lending activities as well as the standards to be
	applied in underwriting and managing credit risk;
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:2PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT">
	Pricing of credit products should be risk-based;
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:2PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT">
	The loan portfolio must be diversified to limit the potential impact of negative events; and
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:2PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT">
	Careful, timely exposure monitoring through dynamic use of our risk rating system is required to provide early warning and assure proactive
	management of potential problems.
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:14PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Commercial Business and Commercial Mortgage Lending
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	We originate commercial business loans in our primary market areas and underwrite them based on the borrower&#146;s ability to service the loan
	from operating income. We offer a broad range of commercial lending products, including term loans and lines of credit. Short and medium-term commercial loans, primarily collateralized, are made available to businesses for working capital (including
	inventory and receivables), business expansion (including acquisition of real estate, expansion and improvements) and the purchase of equipment. We offer commercial business loans to customers in the agricultural industry for short-term crop
	production, farm equipment and livestock financing.&nbsp;As a general practice, where possible, a first position collateral lien is placed on any available real estate, equipment or other assets owned by the borrower and a personal guarantee of the
	owner is obtained.&nbsp;As of December&nbsp;31, 2015, $102.9 million, or 33%, of our aggregate commercial business loan portfolio were at fixed rates, while $210.8 million, or 67%, were at variable rates.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	We also offer commercial mortgage loans to finance the purchase of real property, which generally consists of real estate with completed
	structures and, to a smaller extent, agricultural real estate financing. Commercial mortgage loans are secured by first liens on the real estate and are typically amortized over a 10 to 20 year period. The underwriting analysis includes credit
	verification, appraisals and a review of the borrower&#146;s financial condition and repayment capacity. As of December&nbsp;31, 2015, $238.0 million, or 42%, of the loans in our aggregate commercial mortgage portfolio were at fixed rates, while
	$328.1 million, or 58%, were at variable rates.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	We utilize government loan guarantee programs where available and appropriate.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:14PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Government Guarantee Programs
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	We
	participate in government loan guarantee programs offered by the SBA, U.S. Department of Agriculture, Rural Economic and Community Development and Farm Service Agency, among others.&nbsp;As of December&nbsp;31, 2015, we had loans with an aggregate
	principal balance of $54.3 million that were covered by guarantees under these programs.&nbsp;The guarantees typically only cover a certain percentage of these loans.&nbsp;By participating in these programs, we are able to broaden our base of
	borrowers while minimizing credit risk.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:14PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Residential Mortgage Lending
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	We originate fixed and variable rate one-to-four family residential mortgages collateralized by owner-occupied properties located in our market
	areas.&nbsp;We offer a variety of real estate loan products, which are generally amortized over periods of up to 30 years.&nbsp;Loans collateralized by one-to-four family residential real estate generally have been originated in amounts of no more
	than 80% of appraised value, or have mortgage insurance.&nbsp;Mortgage title insurance and hazard insurance are normally required.&nbsp;We sell certain one-to-four family residential mortgages to the secondary mortgage market and typically retain
	the right to service the mortgages.&nbsp;To assure maximum salability of the residential loan products for possible resale, we typically follow the underwriting and appraisal guidelines of the secondary market, including the FHLMC and the Federal
	Housing Administration, and service the loans in a manner that satisfies the secondary market agreements.&nbsp;As of December&nbsp;31, 2015, our residential mortgage servicing portfolio totaled $196.0 million, the majority of which has been sold to
	the FHLMC.&nbsp;As of December&nbsp;31, 2015, our residential mortgage loan portfolio totaled $98.3 million, or 5% of our total loan portfolio.&nbsp;We do not engage in sub-prime or other high-risk residential mortgage lending as a line-of-business.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	- 7 -
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage8"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D120623D10K_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Consumer Lending
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	We offer a variety of loan products to our consumer customers, including home equity loans and lines of credit, automobile loans, secured
	installment loans and other types of secured and unsecured personal loans.&nbsp;At December&nbsp;31, 2015, outstanding consumer loan balances were concentrated in indirect automobile loans and home equity products, which represented 61% and 37% of
	our outstanding consumer loan balances, respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	We originate indirect consumer loans for a mix of new and used vehicles through
	franchised new car dealers.&nbsp;The consumer indirect loan portfolio is primarily comprised of loans with terms that typically range from 36 to 84 months.&nbsp;We have developed relationships with franchised new car dealers in Western, Central and
	the Capital District of New York, and Northern and Central Pennsylvania.&nbsp;As of December&nbsp;31, 2015, our consumer indirect portfolio totaled $676.9 million, or 33% of our total loan portfolio.&nbsp;The consumer indirect loan portfolio
	primarily consists of fixed rate loans with relatively short durations.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	We also originate, independently of the indirect loans described
	above, consumer automobile loans, recreational vehicle loans, boat loans, home improvement loans, closed-end home equity loans, home equity lines of credit, personal loans (collateralized and uncollateralized) and deposit account collateralized
	loans. The terms of these loans typically range from 12 to 240 months and vary based upon the nature of the collateral and the size of loan. The majority of the consumer lending program is underwritten on a secured basis using the customer&#146;s
	home or the financed automobile, mobile home, boat or recreational vehicle as collateral. As of December&nbsp;31, 2015, $286.5 million, or 70%, of the loans in our home equity portfolio were at fixed rates, while $123.6 million, or 30%, were at
	variable rates. Approximately 82% of the loans in our home equity portfolio were in first lien positions at December&nbsp;31, 2015.&nbsp;The other loans in our consumer portfolio totaled $18.5 million as of December&nbsp;31, 2015, all but $895
	thousand of which were fixed rate loans.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:14PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Credit Administration
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Our loan policy establishes standardized underwriting guidelines, as well as the loan approval process and the committee structures necessary
	to facilitate and ensure the highest possible loan quality decision-making in a timely and businesslike manner.&nbsp;The policy establishes requirements for extending credit based on the size, risk rating and type of credit involved.&nbsp;The policy
	also sets limits on individual loan officer lending authority and various forms of joint lending authority, while designating which loans are required to be approved at the committee level.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Our credit objectives are to:
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT">
	Compete effectively and service the legitimate credit needs of our target market;
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:2PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT">
	Enhance our reputation for superior quality and timely delivery of products and services;
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:2PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT">
	Provide pricing that reflects the entire relationship and is commensurate with the risk profiles of our borrowers;
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:2PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;

<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:2PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT">
	Retain, develop and acquire profitable, multi-product, value added relationships with high quality borrowers;
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:2PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>

	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT">
	Focus on government guaranteed lending and specialize in this area to meet the needs of the small businesses in our communities; and
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:2PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

</TD>

	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT">
	Comply with all relevant laws and regulations.
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Our policy includes loan reviews, under the supervision of our Audit and Risk Oversight committees of the Board of Directors and directed by
	our Chief Risk Officer, in order to render an independent and objective evaluation of our asset quality and credit administration process.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	We assign risk ratings to loans in the commercial business and commercial mortgage portfolios.&nbsp;We use those risk ratings to:
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT">
	Profile the risk and exposure in the loan portfolio and identify developing trends and relative levels of risk;
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:2PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT">
	Identify deteriorating credits;
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:2PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT">
	Reflect the probability that a given customer may default on its obligations; and
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:2PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT">
	Assist with risk-based pricing.
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Through the loan approval process, loan administration and loan review program, management seeks to continuously monitor our credit risk
	profile and assesses the overall quality of the loan portfolio and adequacy of the allowance for loan losses.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	We have several procedures
	in place to assist in maintaining the overall quality of our loan portfolio.&nbsp;Delinquent loan reports are monitored by credit administration to identify adverse levels and trends.&nbsp;Loans, including impaired loans, are generally classified as
	non-accruing if they are past due as to maturity or payment of principal or interest for a period of more than 90 days, unless such loans are well-collateralized and in the process of collection.&nbsp;Loans that are on a current payment status or
	past due less than 90 days may also be classified as non-accruing if repayment in full of principal and/or interest is uncertain.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	- 8 -
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage9"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Allowance for Loan Losses
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The allowance for loan losses is established through charges to earnings in the form of a provision for loan losses. The allowance reflects
	management&#146;s estimate of the amount of probable loan losses in the portfolio, based on factors such as:
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

	Specific allocations for individually analyzed credits;

</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

	&nbsp;

	Customer leverage;
</P>

</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:2PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT">
	Information (availability of timely financial information); and
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:2PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT">
	Collateral values.
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Our methodology for estimating the allowance for loan losses includes the following:
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="1%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	1.
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT">
	Impaired commercial business and commercial mortgage loans, generally in excess of $50 thousand are reviewed individually and assigned a specific
	loss allowance, if considered necessary, in accordance with U.S. generally accepted accounting principles (&#147;GAAP&#148;).
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="1%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	2.
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT">
	The remaining portfolios of commercial business and commercial mortgage loans are segmented by risk rating into the following loan classification
	categories: uncriticized or pass, special mention, substandard and doubtful.&nbsp;Uncriticized loans, special mention loans, substandard loans and all doubtful loans not assigned a specific loss allowance are assigned allowance allocations based on
	historical net loan charge-off experience for each of the respective loan categories, supplemented with additional reserve amounts, if considered necessary, based upon loss emergence periods and qualitative factors.&nbsp;These qualitative factors
	include the levels and trends in delinquent and non-accruing loans, trends in volume and terms of loans, effects of changes in lending policy, experience, ability, and depth of management, national and local economic trends and conditions,
	concentrations of credit, interest rate environment, customer leverage, information (availability of timely financial information), and collateral values, among others.
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="1%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="3%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	3.
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT">
	The retail loan portfolio is segmented into the following types of loans: residential mortgage, home equity (home equity loans and lines of
	credit), consumer indirect and other consumer.&nbsp;Allowance allocations for the retail loan portfolio are based on the average loss experience for the previous eight quarters, supplemented with loss emergence periods and qualitative factors
	similar to the elements described above.
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Management presents a quarterly review of the adequacy of the allowance for
	loan losses to the Audit Committee of our Board of Directors based on the methodology described above. See also the section titled &#147;Allowance for Loan Losses&#148; in Part II, Item 7, &#147;Management&#146;s Discussion and Analysis of Financial
	Condition and Results of Operations&#148; of this Annual Report on Form 10-K.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	- 9 -
</P>

<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D120623D10K_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	SOURCES OF FUNDS
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Our primary sources of funds are deposits, borrowed funds, scheduled amortization and prepayments of principal from loans and mortgage-backed
	securities, maturities and calls of investment securities and funds provided by operations.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:14PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Deposits
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	We maintain a full range of deposit products and accounts to meet the needs of the residents and businesses in our primary service area.
	Products include an array of checking and savings account programs for individuals and businesses, including money market accounts, certificates of deposit, sweep investment capabilities as well as Individual Retirement Accounts and other qualified
	plan accounts.&nbsp;We rely primarily on competitive pricing of our deposit products, customer service and long-standing relationships with customers to attract and retain these deposits and seek to make our services convenient to the community by
	offering a choice of several delivery systems and channels, including telephone, mail, online, automated teller machines (ATMs), debit cards, point-of-sale transactions, automated clearing house transactions (ACH), remote deposit, and mobile banking
	via telephone or wireless devices.&nbsp;We also take advantage of the use of technology by offering business customers banking access via the Internet and various advanced cash management systems.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	We had no traditional brokered deposits at December&nbsp;31, 2015; however, we do participate in the Certificate of Deposit Account Registry
	Service (&#147;CDARS&#148;) and Insured Cash Sweep (&#147;ICS&#148;) programs, which enable depositors to receive FDIC insurance coverage for deposits otherwise exceeding the maximum insurable amount. Through these programs, deposits in excess of
	the maximum insurable amount are placed with multiple participating financial institutions. Reciprocal CDARS deposits and ICS deposits totaled $92.9 million and $146.6 million, respectively, at December&nbsp;31, 2015.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:14PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Borrowings
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	We have access to a variety
	of borrowing sources and use both short-term and long-term borrowings to support our asset base.&nbsp;Borrowings from time-to-time include federal funds purchased, securities sold under agreements to repurchase, FHLB advances and borrowings from the
	discount window of the FRB.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:14PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	OPERATING SEGMENTS
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	As of December&nbsp;31, 2015 we had two reportable operating segments, banking and insurance, which are delineated by the subsidiaries of
	Financial Institutions, Inc. as of December&nbsp;31, 2015. The banking segment includes all of the Company&#146;s retail and commercial banking operations. The insurance segment includes the activities of SDN, a full service insurance agency that
	provides a broad range of insurance services to both personal and business clients. The Company operated as one business segment until the acquisition of SDN on August&nbsp;1, 2014, at which time the new &#147;Insurance&#148; segment was created for
	financial reporting purposes.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	For a discussion of the segments included in our principal activities and certain financial information for
	each segment, see Note 20, Business Segments, of the notes to consolidated financial statements included in this Annual Report on Form 10-K.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:14PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">

	8-K, as well as any amendments thereto may be accessed at
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" COLOR="#0000FF">
<U>
	www.sec.gov
</U>
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
	or at the public reference facility maintained by the SEC at its
	public reference room at 100 F. Street, N.E., Room 1580, Washington, DC 20549 and copies of all or any part thereof may be obtained from that office upon payment of the prescribed fees.&nbsp;You may call the SEC at 1-800-SEC-0330 for further
	information on the operation of the public reference room and you can request copies of the documents upon payment of a duplicating fee, by writing to the SEC.
</FONT>
</P>

<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D120623D10K_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	SUPERVISION AND REGULATION
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The Company and our subsidiaries are subject to extensive regulation under federal and state laws. The regulatory framework is intended
	primarily for the protection of depositors, federal deposit insurance funds and the banking system as a whole and not for the protection of shareholders and creditors.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	We are also subject to the disclosure and regulatory requirements of the Securities Act of 1933, as amended, and the Securities Exchange Act of
	1934, as amended, as administered by the Securities and Exchange Commission (&#147;SEC&#148;). Our common stock is listed on the NASDAQ Global Select Market (&#147;NASDAQ&#148;) under the trading symbol &#147;FISI&#148; and is subject to NASDAQ
	rules for listed companies.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Significant elements of the laws and regulations applicable to the Company and its subsidiaries are described
	below. The description is qualified in its entirety by reference to the full text of the statutes, regulations and policies that are described. Also, such statutes, regulations and policies are continually under review by Congress, state
	legislatures, and federal and state regulatory agencies. A change in statutes, regulations or regulatory policies applicable to the Company and its subsidiaries could have a material effect on the business, financial condition and results of
	operations of the Company.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:14PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
<B>
	Holding Company Regulation
</B>
	.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We are subject to comprehensive regulation by the Board of
	Governors of the Federal Reserve System, frequently referred to as the Federal Reserve Board (&#147;FRB&#148;), under the Bank Holding Company Act (the &#147;BHC Act&#148;), as amended by, among other laws, the Gramm-Leach-Bliley Act of 1999 (the
	&#147;Gramm-Leach-Bliley Act&#148;), and by the Dodd-Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act (the &#147;Dodd-Frank Act&#148;), enacted in 2010. We are registered with the Federal Reserve as a bank holding company (&#147;BHC&#148;) and
	have elected to be treated as a financial holding company under the BHC Act. We must file reports with the FRB and such additional information as the FRB may require, and our holding company and non-banking affiliates are subject to examination by
	the FRB.&nbsp;Under FRB policy, a bank holding company must serve as a source of strength for its subsidiary banks. Under this policy, the FRB may require, and has required in the past, a holding company to contribute additional capital to an
	undercapitalized subsidiary bank. The BHC Act provides that a bank holding company must obtain FRB approval before:
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT">
	Acquiring, directly or indirectly, ownership or control of any voting shares of another bank or bank holding company if, after such acquisition, it
	would own or control more than 5% of such shares (unless it already owns or controls the majority of such shares);
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:2PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT">
	Acquiring all or substantially all of the assets of another bank or bank holding company, or
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:2PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT">
	Merging or consolidating with another bank holding company.
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The BHC Act generally prohibits a bank holding company from acquiring direct or indirect ownership or control of more than 5% of the voting
	shares of any company which is not a bank or bank holding company, or from engaging directly or indirectly in activities other than those of banking, managing or controlling banks, or providing services for its subsidiaries. The principal exceptions
	to these prohibitions involve certain non-bank activities which, by statute or by FRB regulation or order, have been identified as activities closely related to the business of banking or managing or controlling banks. The list of activities
	permitted by the FRB includes, among other things: lending; operating a savings institution, mortgage company, finance company, credit card company or factoring company; performing certain data processing operations; providing certain investment and
	financial advice; underwriting and acting as an insurance agent for certain types of credit related insurance; leasing property on a full-payout, non-operating basis; selling money orders, travelers&#146; checks and United States Savings Bonds; real
	estate and personal property appraising; providing tax planning and preparation services; and, subject to certain limitations, providing securities brokerage services for customers. These activities may also be affected by federal legislation.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The Gramm-Leach-Bliley Act amended portions of the BHC Act to authorize bank holding companies, such as us, directly or through non-bank
	subsidiaries to engage in securities, insurance and other activities that are financial in nature or incidental to a financial activity. In order to undertake these activities, a bank holding company must become a &#147;financial holding
	company&#148; by submitting to the appropriate Federal Reserve Bank a declaration that the company elects to be a financial holding company and a certification that all of the depository institutions controlled by the company are well capitalized
	and well managed.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
<B>
	The Dodd-Frank Act.
</B>
<B>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;
</B>
	The Dodd-Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act (the
	&#147;Dodd-Frank Act&#148;), which was signed into law in 2010, significantly changes the regulation of financial institutions and the financial services industry. The Dodd-Frank Act includes provisions affecting large and small financial
	institutions alike, including several provisions that will profoundly affect how community banks, thrifts, and small bank and thrift holding companies will be regulated in the future. Among other things, these provisions abolish the Office of Thrift
	Supervision and transfer its functions to the other federal banking agencies, relax rules regarding interstate branching, allow financial institutions to pay interest on business checking accounts, and impose new capital requirements on bank and
	thrift holding companies. The Dodd-Frank Act also includes several corporate governance provisions that apply to all public companies, not just financial institutions. These include provisions mandating certain disclosures regarding executive
	compensation and provisions addressing proxy access by shareholders.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	- 11 -
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage12"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D120623D10K_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The Dodd-Frank Act contains numerous other provisions affecting financial institutions of all
	types, including some that may affect our business in substantial and unpredictable ways. We have incurred higher operating costs in complying with the Dodd -Frank Act, and we expect that these higher costs will continue for the foreseeable future.
	Our management continues to monitor the ongoing implementation of the Dodd-Frank Act and as new regulations are issued, will assess their effect on our business, financial condition, and results of operations.&nbsp;See Item 1A, Risk Factors, for a
	more extensive discussion of this topic.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:14PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
<B>
	The Volcker Rule.
</B>
<B>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;
</B>
	The Dodd-Frank act prohibits banks and their
	affiliates from engaging in proprietary trading and from investing and sponsoring hedge funds and private equity funds. The statutory provision implementing these restrictions is commonly called the &#147;Volcker Rule.&#148; To implement the Volcker
	Rule, federal regulators issued final rules in December&nbsp;2013 that were to become effective April&nbsp;2014. The Federal Reserve subsequently issued an order extending the period that institutions have to conform their activities to the
	requirements of the Volcker Rule to July&nbsp;21, 2015, and extended the compliance date for banks to conform their investments in certain &#147;legacy covered funds&#148; until July&nbsp;21, 2016. These final rules exempt the Bank, as a bank with
	less than $10 billion in total consolidated assets that does not engage in any covered activities other than trading in certain government, agency, state or municipal obligations, from any significant compliance obligations under the Volcker Rule;
	therefore, the Volcker rule will not have a material effect on our business, financial condition and results of operations.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:14PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
<B>
	Depository
	Institution Regulation.
</B>
<B>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</B>
	The Bank is subject to regulation by the FDIC.&nbsp;This regulatory structure includes:
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT">
	Real estate lending standards, which provide guidelines concerning loan-to-value ratios for various types of real estate loans;
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:2PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
<TD WIDTH="4%">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="TOP" ALIGN="LEFT">
	&#149;
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="TOP">
	&nbsp;
</TD>
<TD ALIGN="LEFT" VALIGN="TOP">
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT">
	Risk-based capital rules, including accounting for interest rate risk, concentration of credit risk and the risks posed by non-traditional
	activities;
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:2PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY" STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT">
	Rules requiring depository institutions to develop and implement internal procedures to evaluate and control credit and settlement exposure to
	their correspondent banks;
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:2PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>

	&nbsp;
</TD>

</TD>

</TD>

	Rules restricting types and amounts of equity investments; and
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:2PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN; FONT-SIZE:10PT" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
