<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D120623D10K_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
<B>
	MANAGEMENT&#146;S DISCUSSION AND ANALYSIS
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Income Taxes
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	We recorded income tax expense of $10.5 million for 2015, compared to $9.6 million for 2014.&nbsp;Our effective tax rate was 27.1% for 2015
	compared to 24.7% for 2014.&nbsp;Effective tax rates are impacted by items of income and expense that are not subject to federal or state taxation.&nbsp;Our effective tax rates reflect the impact of these items, which include, but are not limited
	to, interest income from tax-exempt securities and earnings on company owned life insurance.&nbsp;In addition, the lower effective tax rate in 2014 reflects the previously mentioned historic tax credit benefit.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	In March&nbsp;2014, the New York legislature approved changes in the state tax law to be phased-in over two years, beginning in 2015. The
	primary changes that impact us include the repeal of the Article 32 franchise tax on banking corporations (&#147;Article 32&#148;) for 2015, expanded nexus standards for 2015 and a reduction in the corporate tax rate for 2016. We expect the repeal
	of Article 32 and the expanded nexus standards to lower our taxable income apportioned to New York in 2015 compared to 2014. In addition, the New York state income tax rate will be reduced from 7.1% to 6.5% in 2016.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:26PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	RESULTS OF OPERATIONS FOR THE YEARS ENDED
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	DECEMBER&nbsp;31, 2014 AND DECEMBER&nbsp;31, 2013
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:14PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Net Interest Income and Net Interest Margin
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Net interest income was $93.8 million in 2014, compared to $91.6 million in 2013.&nbsp;The taxable equivalent adjustments of $2.8 million and
	$2.6 million for 2014 and 2013, respectively, resulted in fully taxable equivalent net interest income of $96.6 million in 2014 and $94.2 million in 2013.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	During the first quarter of 2014, we utilized the proceeds of short-term Federal Home Loan Bank (&#147;FHLB&#148;) advances to purchase
	investment securities of approximately $50 million (the &#147;2014 leverage strategy&#148;). During the second quarter of 2014 we sold approximately $42 million of securities purchased in the first quarter and utilized the proceeds to fund growth in
	our home equity portfolio. During the third quarter of 2014, we utilized the proceeds of short-term FHLB advances to purchase an additional $25 million of investment securities. Our purchases of investment securities were comprised of high-quality
	mortgage-backed securities, U.S. Government agencies and sponsored enterprise bonds and tax-exempt municipal bonds.&nbsp;All of the securities purchased were of high credit quality with a low to moderate duration. This strategy allowed us to
	increase net interest income by taking advantage of the positive interest rate spread between the FHLB advances and the newly acquired investment securities.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Taxable-equivalent net interest income for 2014 increased $2.4 million or 3%, compared to 2013. The increase primarily related to an increase
	in the average volume of interest-earning assets. The average volume of interest-earning assets for 2014 increased $174.3 million or 7% compared to 2013. The increase in earning assets was primarily due to a $130.9 million increase in average loans
	and a $43.5 million increase in average investment securities.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The net interest margin for 2014 was 3.50% compared to 3.64% in
	2013.&nbsp;The net interest margin during 2014 was positively impacted by an increase in the yield on average securities, which resulted from an increase in the relative proportion of higher-yielding tax-exempt municipal securities relative to
	lower-yielding taxable securities, combined with a decrease in the cost of average interest-bearing liabilities. The net interest margin was negatively impacted by a decrease in the average yield on loans. These items are more fully discussed below.
	The yield on average interest-earning assets decreased 17 basis points to 3.76% during 2014 from 3.93% during 2013 while the cost of average interest-bearing liabilities decreased 2 basis points from 0.36% during 2013 to 0.34% during 2014. The yield
	on average interest-earning assets is primarily impacted by changes in market interest rates as well as changes in the volume and relative mix of interest-earning assets. As stated above, market interest rates have remained at historically low
	levels during the reported periods.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The average balance of securities increased $43.5 million or 5% in 2014, compared to
	2013.&nbsp;Securities made up 31.8% of average interest-earning assets in 2014 compared to 32.3% in 2013.&nbsp;The yield on average securities was 2.44% in 2014 compared to 2.41% in 2013.&nbsp;The yield on average securities increased 3 basis points
	during 2014 compared to 2013 as we increased the relative proportion of investments held in higher-yielding, tax-exempt municipal securities.&nbsp;The relative proportion of higher-yielding, tax-exempt municipal securities to total average
	securities totaled 29.6% in 2014 compared to 27.9% in 2013.&nbsp;The yield on average taxable securities was 2.15% in 2014 compared to 2.09% in 2013, while the taxable-equivalent yield on average tax-exempt securities was 3.14% in 2014 compared to
	3.25% in 2013.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The average volume of loans increased $130.9 million or 7% in 2014, compared to 2013.&nbsp;Loans made up 68.2% of average
	interest-earning assets during 2014 compared to 67.7% during 2013.&nbsp;Loans generally have significantly higher yields compared to securities and federal funds sold and interest-bearing deposits and, as such, have a more positive effect on the net
	interest margin. The yield on average loans was 4.38% during 2014 compared to 4.65% during 2013. The yield on average loans decreased 27 basis points during 2014 compared to 2013.&nbsp;The yield on average loans was negatively impacted by lower
	average spreads due to increased competition in loan pricing during 2014 compared to 2013.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	- 41 -
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage42"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D120623D10K_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
<B>
	MANAGEMENT&#146;S DISCUSSION AND ANALYSIS
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Average deposits increased $111.9 million or 5% in 2014, compared to 2013.&nbsp;Average
	interest-bearing deposits increased $75.4 million in 2014 compared to 2013, while average non-interest-bearing deposits increased $36.5 million in 2014 compared to 2013.&nbsp;The ratio of average interest-bearing deposits to total average deposits
	was 77.8% in 2014 compared to 78.3% in 2013. The cost of average interest-bearing deposits was 0.33% in 2014 compared to 0.36% in 2013.&nbsp;The decrease in the average cost of interest-bearing deposits during the comparable periods was primarily
	the result of decreases in interest rates offered on certain deposit products due to the low interest rate environment. Additionally, the relative proportion of higher-cost time deposits to total average interest-bearing deposits decreased to 32.6%
	in 2014 from 33.8% in 2013.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:14PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Provision for Loan Losses
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The provision for loan losses was $7.8 million for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2014 compared with $9.1 million for 2013.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:14PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Noninterest Income
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Service charges on
	deposits were $9.0 million for 2014, a decrease of $1.0 million or 10%, compared to 2013.&nbsp;Service charges on deposit accounts for 2013 reflected a retail checking account repositioning that involved simplifying the suite of products offered to
	customers and modifications to the fee structure for our accounts.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	ATM and debit card income for 2014 decreased $135 thousand or 3%
	compared to 2013.&nbsp;The decrease is primarily attributable to lower transaction volumes due to card reissuances associated with third-party security breaches.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Insurance income of $2.4 million for 2014 was up $2.1 million from 2013, reflecting 5 months of income from the SDN acquisition.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Investment advisory income was $2.1 million for 2014, down $207 thousand or 9%, compared to 2013, as fees and commissions fluctuate with sales
	volume.&nbsp;Sales volume during 2014 was negatively impacted by a longer-than-anticipated conversion to a new clearing platform that began in late 2013.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Income from investments in limited partnerships was $1.1 million and $857 thousand for the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2014 and 2013,
	respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Gains from the sale of loans held for sale increased $196 thousand in 2014 compared to 2013.&nbsp;The increase was primarily
	due to higher margins due to the timing of sales and fluctuation of interest rates during the year.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	During the year ended
	December&nbsp;31, 2014 we recognized gains of $2.0 million from the sale of AFS securities with an amortized cost totaling $79.6 million.&nbsp;The securities sold were comprised of one pooled trust preferred security, three mortgage backed
	securities and 20 agency securities.&nbsp;During 2013, we recognized gains totaling $1.2 million from the sale of four pooled trust-preferred securities.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	During the fourth quarter of 2014 we recorded $2.3 million for the amortization, recognized as contra-income, of a historic tax investment in a
	community-based project.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Other noninterest income increased $565 thousand or 20% for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2014, compared to
	2013.&nbsp;Merchant services income, dividends on FHLB stock and credit card correspondent income comprised the majority of the year-over-year increases.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:14PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Noninterest Expense
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Salaries and
	employee benefits increased by $767 thousand or 2% when comparing 2014 to 2013.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;An increase of $1.5 million in salaries expense was primarily due to the acquisition of SDN and the hiring of additional loan officers, partially
	offset by a decrease in severance expense.&nbsp;A decrease of $765 thousand in employee benefits was primarily due to lower expense related to our defined benefit retirement plan, partially offset by higher medical expenses. We recognized a combined
	net periodic pension and post-retirement expense of $222 thousand during 2014 compared to $1.7 million during 2013.&nbsp;The number of full time equivalent employees increased to 622 at December&nbsp;31, 2014 from 608 at December&nbsp;31, 2013.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Occupancy and equipment increased by $463 thousand or 4% when comparing 2014 to 2013.&nbsp;The increase was primarily related to higher
	contractual service expenses and incremental expenses from the SDN facility.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Professional services expense of $4.8 million in 2014
	increased $924 thousand or 24% from 2013. The increases were largely due to professional services associated with the acquisition of SDN, the hiring of additional loan officers and related personnel as part of our expansion initiatives and other
	special projects.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Computer and data processing increased by $168 thousand or 6% when comparing 2014 to 2013.&nbsp;During late 2013, we
	ceased operations of our broker-dealer subsidiary and transferred the existing business to an outsourced clearing platform, resulting in higher third-party processing expense.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	- 42 -
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage43"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D120623D10K_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
<B>
	MANAGEMENT&#146;S DISCUSSION AND ANALYSIS
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Supplies and postage and advertising and promotions expense decreased, collectively, by $380
	thousand when comparing 2014 to 2013.&nbsp;The prior year amounts included expenses for additional print materials related to our retail checking account repositioning incurred during the first quarter of 2013.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	FDIC assessments increased $128 thousand or 9% for the year ended December 31, 2014, compared to 2013.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The increase in
	assessments is a direct result of the growth in our balance sheet.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Other noninterest expense increased $844 thousand or 11% when comparing
	2014 to 2013.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The increase was largely due to higher intangible asset amortization due to the SDN acquisition, combined with an increase in electronic banking activities and deposit expenses.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The efficiency ratio for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2014 was 58.59% compared with 58.48% for 2013.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Income Taxes
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	We recorded income tax
	expense of $9.6 million for 2014, compared to of $12.4 million for 2013.&nbsp;Our effective tax rate was 24.7% for 2014 compared to 32.7% for 2013.&nbsp;The lower effective tax rate in 2014 reflects the historic tax credit benefit described above
	combined with New York State tax savings generated by our real estate investment trust, which became effective during February&nbsp;2014 and is discussed below.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	During February&nbsp;2014, the Bank formed a wholly-owned subsidiary, Five Star REIT, Inc. (the &#147;REIT&#148;), to acquire a portion of the
	Bank&#146;s assets, which were primarily qualifying mortgage related&nbsp;loans.&nbsp;The Bank made an initial contribution of mortgage related loans to the REIT in return for common stock of the REIT. The REIT has and expects to continue purchasing
	mortgage related loans from the Bank on a periodic basis going forward.&nbsp;The REIT entered into service agreements with the Bank for administrative and investment services. The formation of the REIT reduced 2014 tax expense by approximately $950
	thousand.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	- 43 -
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage44"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D120623D10K_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
<B>
	MANAGEMENT&#146;S DISCUSSION AND ANALYSIS
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
<I>
	ANALYSIS OF FINANCIAL CONDITION
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:14PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	OVERVIEW
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	At December&nbsp;31, 2015, we
	had total assets of $3.38 billion, an increase of 9% from $3.09 billion as of December&nbsp;31, 2014, largely attributable to our continued loan growth and higher investment security balances.&nbsp;Net loans were $2.06 billion as of
	December&nbsp;31, 2015, up $172.3 million or 9%, when compared to $1.88 billion as of December&nbsp;31, 2014.&nbsp;The increase in net loans was primarily attributable to organic growth in the commercial portfolio.&nbsp;Non-performing assets totaled
	$8.6 million as of December&nbsp;31, 2015, down $1.7 million from a year ago. Total deposits amounted to $2.73 billion as of December&nbsp;31, 2015, up $280.0 million or 11%, compared to December&nbsp;31, 2014. As of December&nbsp;31, 2015, borrowed
	funds totaled $332.1 million, compared to $334.8 million as of December&nbsp;31, 2014. Common book value per common share was $19.49 and $18.57 as of December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, respectively. As of December&nbsp;31, 2015 our total
	shareholders&#146; equity was $293.8 million compared to $279.5 million a year earlier.
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Our investment policy is contained within our overall Asset-Liability Management and Investment
	Policy.&nbsp;This policy dictates that investment decisions will be made based on the safety of the investment, liquidity requirements, potential returns, cash flow targets, need for collateral and desired risk parameters.&nbsp;In pursuing these
	objectives, we consider the ability of an investment to provide earnings consistent with factors of quality, maturity, marketability, pledgeable nature and risk diversification.&nbsp;Our Treasurer, guided by ALCO, is responsible for investment
	portfolio decisions within the established policies.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	During the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, we transferred $165.2 million
	and $12.8 million, respectively, of available for sale (&#147;AFS&#148;) mortgage backed securities to the held to maturity (&#147;HTM&#148;) category, reflecting our intent to hold those securities to maturity. Transfers of investment securities
	into the held to maturity category from the available for sale category are made at fair value at the date of transfer. The related $1.1 million and $51 thousand of unrealized holding losses that were included in the transfers during the years ended
	December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, respectively, are retained in accumulated other comprehensive income and in the carrying value of the held to maturity securities. These amounts will be amortized as an adjustment to interest income over the
	remaining life of the securities. This will offset the impact of amortization of the net premium created in the transfers. There were no gains or losses recognized as a result of this transfer.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Our AFS investment securities portfolio decreased $78.1 million to $544.4 million at December&nbsp;31, 2015 from $622.5 million at
	December&nbsp;31, 2014.&nbsp;The decrease was due to the transfer of securities from the AFS portfolio to the HTM portfolio described above. Our AFS portfolio had a net unrealized gain totaling $774 thousand at December&nbsp;31, 2015 compared to a
	net unrealized gain of $3.2 million at December&nbsp;31, 2014.&nbsp;The fair value of most of the investment securities in the AFS portfolio fluctuates as market interest rates change.&nbsp;The transfers of securities from AFS to HTM are expected to
	reduce the fair value fluctuations in the available for sale portfolio.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	During the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, we recognized gains
	of $2.0 million from the sale of AFS securities with an amortized cost totaling $52.3 million.&nbsp;The securities sold were comprised of 5 agency securities and 13 mortgage backed securities.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	- 44 -

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
<B>
	MANAGEMENT&#146;S DISCUSSION AND ANALYSIS
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Impairment Assessment
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	We review investment securities on an ongoing basis for the presence of other-than-temporary impairment (&#147;OTTI&#148;) with formal reviews
	performed quarterly. Declines in the fair value of held to maturity and available for sale securities below their cost that are deemed to be other than temporary are reflected in earnings as realized losses to the extent the impairment is related to
	credit losses or the security is intended to be sold or will be required to be sold.&nbsp;The amount of the impairment related to non-credit related factors is recognized in other comprehensive income.&nbsp;Evaluating whether the impairment of a
	debt security is other than temporary involves assessing i.) the intent to sell the debt security or ii.) the likelihood of being required to sell the security before the recovery of its amortized cost basis.&nbsp;In determining whether the OTTI
	includes a credit loss, we use our best estimate of the present value of cash flows expected to be collected from the debt security considering factors such as: a.) the length of time and the extent to which the fair value has been less than the
	amortized cost basis, b.) adverse conditions specifically related to the security, an industry, or a geographic area, c.) the historical and implied volatility of the fair value of the security, d.) the payment structure of the debt security and the
	likelihood of the issuer being able to make payments that increase in the future, e.) failure of the issuer of the security to make scheduled interest or principal payments, f.) any changes to the rating of the security by a rating agency, and g.)
	recoveries or additional declines in fair value subsequent to the balance sheet date.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	As of December&nbsp;31, 2015, we do not have the
	intent to sell any of our securities in a loss position and we believe that it is not likely that we will be required to sell any such securities before the anticipated recovery of amortized cost.&nbsp;The unrealized losses are largely due to
	increases in market interest rates over the yields available at the time the underlying securities were purchased.&nbsp;The fair value is expected to recover as the bonds approach their maturity date, repricing date or if market yields for such
	investments decline.&nbsp;We do not believe any of the securities in a loss position are impaired due to reasons of credit quality. Accordingly, as of December&nbsp;31, 2015, we concluded that unrealized losses on our investment securities are
	temporary and no further impairment loss has been realized in our consolidated statements of income.&nbsp;The following discussion provides further details of our assessment of the securities portfolio by investment category.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
<B>
	U.S. Government Agencies and Government Sponsored Enterprises (&#147;GSE&#148;).&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</B>
	As of December&nbsp;31, 2015, there
	were 29 securities in an unrealized loss position in the U.S. Government agencies and GSE portfolio with unrealized losses totaling $1.0 million.&nbsp;Of these, 6 were in an unrealized loss position for 12 months or longer and had an aggregate fair
	value of $26.3 million and unrealized losses of $314 thousand. The decline in fair value is attributable to changes in interest rates, and not credit quality, and because we do not have the intent to sell these securities and it is likely that we
	will not be required to sell the securities before their anticipated recovery, we do not consider these securities to be other-than-temporarily impaired at December&nbsp;31, 2015.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
<B>
	State and Political Subdivisions.
</B>
<B>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</B>
	As of December&nbsp;31, 2015, the state and political subdivisions
	(&#147;municipal securities&#148;) portfolio totaled $294.4 million, all of which was classified as HTM. As of that date, each of the 7 municipal securities in an unrealized loss position had been in an unrealized loss position for less than 12
	months.&nbsp;Those securities had an aggregate fair value of $3.1 million and unrealized losses totaling $4 thousand.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The decline in fair
	value is attributable to changes in interest rates, and not credit quality, and because we do not have the intent to sell these securities and it is not likely that we will be required to sell the securities before their anticipated recovery, we do
	not consider these securities to be other-than-temporarily impaired at December&nbsp;31, 2015.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
<B>
	Agency Mortgage-backed
	Securities.
</B>
<B>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</B>
	With the exception of the non-Agency mortgage-backed securities (&#147;non-Agency MBS&#148;) discussed below, all of the mortgage-backed securities held by us as of December&nbsp;31, 2015, were issued by
	U.S. Government sponsored entities and agencies (&#147;Agency MBS&#148;), primarily FNMA and FHLMC.&nbsp;The contractual cash flows of our Agency MBS are guaranteed by FNMA, FHLMC or GNMA.&nbsp;The GNMA mortgage-backed securities are backed by the
	full faith and credit of the U.S. Government.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	As of December&nbsp;31, 2015, there were 52 securities in the AFS Agency MBS portfolio that
	were in an unrealized loss position.&nbsp;Of these, 4 were in an unrealized loss position for 12 months or longer and had an aggregate fair value of $9.6 million and unrealized losses of $199 thousand.&nbsp;As of December&nbsp;31, 2015, each of the
	64 securities in the HTM Agency MBS portfolio that were in an unrealized loss position had been in an unrealized loss position for less than 12 months.&nbsp;Those securities had an aggregate fair value of $164.3 million and unrealized losses
	totaling $2.3 million.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Given the high credit quality inherent in Agency MBS, we do not consider any of the unrealized losses as of
	December&nbsp;31, 2015 on such MBS to be credit related or other-than-temporary.&nbsp;As of December&nbsp;31, 2015, we did not intend to sell any Agency MBS that were in an unrealized loss position, all of which were performing in accordance with
	their terms.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
<B>
	Non-Agency Mortgage-backed Securities.
</B>
<B>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;
</B>
	Our non-Agency MBS portfolio consists of positions in two
	privately issued whole loan collateralized mortgage obligations with a fair value and net unrealized gains of $809 thousand as of December&nbsp;31, 2015.&nbsp;As of that date, each of the two non-Agency MBS were rated below investment
	grade.&nbsp;None of these securities were in an unrealized loss position.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
<B>
	Asset-backed Securities (&#147;ABS&#148;).&nbsp;&nbsp;
</B>
	Our
	ABS portfolio consisted of one security with a fair value and unrealized gain of $218 thousand as of December&nbsp;31, 2015.&nbsp;As of December&nbsp;31, 2015, the ABS security was rated below investment grade.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	- 45 -
</P>

<B>
	MANAGEMENT&#146;S DISCUSSION AND ANALYSIS

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
<B>
	Other Investments.&nbsp;&nbsp;
</B>
	As
<B>
</B>
	a member of the FHLB, the Bank is required to
	hold FHLB stock. The amount of required FHLB stock is based on the Bank&#146;s asset size and the amount of borrowings from the FHLB. We have assessed the ultimate recoverability of our FHLB stock and believe that no impairment currently exists. As
	a member of the FRB system, we are required to maintain a specified investment in FRB stock based on a ratio relative to our capital. At December&nbsp;31, 2015, our ownership of FHLB and FRB stock totaled $15.1 million and $4.9 million, respectively
	and is included in other assets and recorded at cost, which approximates fair value.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:20PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	LENDING ACTIVITIES
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Total loans were $2.08 billion at December&nbsp;31, 2015, an increase of $171.8 million or 9% from December&nbsp;31, 2014.&nbsp;Commercial
	loans increased $7.5 million and represented 38.9% of total loans at the end of 2014.&nbsp;Residential mortgage loans were $100.1 million, down $12.9 million or 11% and represented 5.2% of total loans at December&nbsp;31, 2014, while consumer loans
	increased $83.9 million to represent 55.9% of total loans at December&nbsp;31, 2014.&nbsp;The composition of our loan portfolio, excluding loans held for sale and including net unearned income and net deferred fees and costs, is summarized as
	follows (in thousands):
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">

</EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Commercial loans increased during 2015 as we continued our commercial business development efforts.&nbsp;The
	credit risk related to commercial loans is largely influenced by general economic conditions and the resulting impact on a borrower&#146;s operations or on the value of underlying collateral.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	We participate in various lending programs in which guarantees are supplied by U.S. government agencies, such as the SBA, U.S. Department of
	Agriculture, Rural Economic and Community Development and Farm Service Agency, among others.&nbsp;As of December&nbsp;31, 2015, the principal balance of such loans (included in commercial loans) was $54.3 million and the guaranteed portion amounted
	to $35.9 million.&nbsp;Most of these loans were guaranteed by the SBA.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Commercial business loans were $313.8 million at the end of 2015,
	up $46.3 million or 17% since the end of 2014, and comprised 15.0% of total loans outstanding at December&nbsp;31, 2015, compared to 14.0% at December&nbsp;31, 2014.&nbsp;We typically originate business loans of up to $15.0 million for small to
	mid-sized businesses in our market area for working capital, equipment financing, inventory financing, accounts receivable financing, or other general business purposes.&nbsp;Loans of this type are in a diverse range of industries.&nbsp;Within the
	commercial business classification, loans to finance agricultural production totaled approximately 7% of commercial business loans as of December&nbsp;31, 2015.&nbsp;As of December&nbsp;31, 2015, commercial business SBA loans accounted for a total
	of $35.4 million or 11% of our commercial business loan portfolio.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Commercial mortgage loans totaled $566.1 million at December&nbsp;31,
	2015, up $91.0 million or 19% from December&nbsp;31, 2014, and comprised 27.2% of total loans, compared to 24.9% at December&nbsp;31, 2014.&nbsp;Commercial mortgage loans include both owner occupied and non-owner occupied commercial real estate
	loans.&nbsp;Approximately 41% and 45% of our commercial mortgage portfolio at December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, respectively, was owner occupied commercial real estate.&nbsp;The majority of our commercial real estate loans are secured by office
	buildings, manufacturing facilities, distribution/warehouse facilities, and retail centers, which are generally located in our local market area.&nbsp;As of December&nbsp;31, 2015, commercial mortgage SBA loans accounted for a total of $14.0 million
	or 2% of our commercial mortgage loan portfolio.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	We determine our current lending standards for commercial real estate and real estate
	construction lending by property type and specifically address many criteria, including: maximum loan amounts, maximum loan-to-value (&#147;LTV&#148;), requirements for pre-leasing or pre-sales, minimum debt-service coverage ratios, minimum borrower
	equity, and maximum loan to cost. Currently, the maximum standard for LTV is 85%, with lower limits established for certain higher risk types, such as raw land which has a 65% LTV maximum.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	- 46 -
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage47"></A>
<P STYLE='PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS'>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D120623D10K_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
<B>
	MANAGEMENT&#146;S DISCUSSION AND ANALYSIS
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Residential mortgage loans totaled $98.3 million at the end of 2015, down $1.8 million or 2%
	from the end of the prior year and comprised 4.7% of total loans outstanding at December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 5.2% at December&nbsp;31, 2014. Residential mortgage loans include conventional first lien home mortgages. We generally limit the maximum loan
	to 85% of collateral value without credit enhancement (e.g. personal mortgage insurance). As part of management&#146;s historical practice of originating and servicing residential mortgage loans, the majority of our fixed-rate residential mortgage
	loans are sold in the secondary market with servicing rights retained. Residential mortgage products continue to be underwritten using FHLMC and FNMA secondary marketing guidelines.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	As of December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, our residential mortgage portfolio included $12.8 million and $15.7 million, respectively, of loans
	acquired during the 2012 branch acquisitions and $85.5 million and $84.4 million of organic loans, respectively. Over the past several years we&#146;ve placed less emphasis on expanding our residential mortgage loan portfolio while strategically
	increasing our consumer indirect and home equity loan portfolios. In addition, it has been our practice to sell the majority of our fixed-rate residential mortgages in the secondary market with servicing rights retained.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Consumer loans totaled $1.11 billion at December&nbsp;31, 2015, up $36.2 million or 3% compared to 2014, and represented 53.1% of the 2015
	year-end loan portfolio versus 55.9% at year-end 2014.&nbsp;Loans in this classification include indirect consumer, home equity and other consumer installment loans.&nbsp;Credit risk for these types of loans is generally influenced by general
	economic conditions, the characteristics of individual borrowers, and the nature of the loan collateral.&nbsp;Risks of loss are generally on smaller average balances per loan spread over many borrowers.&nbsp;Once charged off, there is usually less
	opportunity for recovery on these smaller retail loans. Credit risk is primarily controlled by reviewing the creditworthiness of the borrowers, monitoring payment histories, and taking appropriate collateral and guaranty positions.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The home equity portfolio consists of both lines of credit and loans.&nbsp;Home equities amounted to $410.1 million at December&nbsp;31, 2015
	up $23.5 million or 6% compared to 2014, and represented 19.7% of the 2015 year-end loan portfolio versus 20.2% at year-end 2014.&nbsp;The portfolio had a weighted average LTV at origination of approximately 58% and 57% at December&nbsp;31, 2015 and
	2014, respectively.&nbsp;Approximately 82% and 80% of the loans in the home equity portfolio were first lien positions at December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, respectively.&nbsp;We continue to grow our home equity portfolio as the lower origination cost
	and convenience to customers has made these products an increasingly attractive alternative to conventional residential mortgage loans.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Our underwriting guidelines for home equity products includes a combination of borrower FICO (credit score), the LTV of the property securing
	the loan and evidence of the borrower having sufficient income to repay the loan.&nbsp;Currently, for home equity products, the maximum acceptable LTV is 90%.&nbsp;The average FICO score for new home equity production was 753 and 751 during the
	years ended December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Consumer indirect loans amounted to $676.9 million at December&nbsp;31, 2015 up
	$15.3 million or 2% compared to 2014, and represented 32.5% of the 2015 year-end loan portfolio versus 34.6% at year-end 2014.&nbsp;The loans are primarily for the purchase of automobiles (both new and used) and light duty trucks primarily by
	individuals, but also by corporations and other organizations.&nbsp;The loans are originated through dealerships and assigned to us with terms that typically range from 36 to 84 months.&nbsp;During the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, we
	originated $296.9 million in indirect loans with a mix of approximately 40% new vehicles and 60% used vehicles.&nbsp;This compares with $305.6 million in indirect loans with a mix of approximately 41% new vehicles and 59% used vehicles for the same
	period in 2014.&nbsp;We do business with over 400 franchised auto dealers located in Western, Central, and the Capital District of New York, and Northern and Central Pennsylvania.&nbsp;The average FICO score for new indirect loan production was 728
	and 722 during the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, respectively.&nbsp;Other consumer loans totaled $18.5 million at December&nbsp;31, 2015, down $2.6 million or 12% compared to 2014, and represented less than one percent of the 2015
	year-end loan portfolio versus 1.1% at year-end 2014.&nbsp;Other consumer loans consist of personal loans (collateralized and uncollateralized) and deposit account collateralized loans.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Factors that are important to managing overall credit quality are sound loan underwriting and administration, systematic monitoring of existing
	loans and commitments, effective loan review on an ongoing basis, early identification of potential problems, an appropriate allowance for loan losses, and sound nonaccrual and charge off policies.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	An active credit risk management process is used for commercial loans to further ensure that sound and consistent credit decisions are made.
	Credit risk is controlled by detailed underwriting procedures, comprehensive loan administration, and periodic review of borrowers&#146; outstanding loans and commitments. Borrower relationships are formally reviewed and graded on an ongoing basis
	for early identification of potential problems. Further analyses by customer, industry, and geographic location are performed to monitor trends, financial performance, and concentrations.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Our loan portfolio is widely diversified by types of borrowers, industry groups, and market areas within our core footprint. Significant loan
	concentrations are considered to exist for a financial institution when there are amounts loaned to numerous borrowers engaged in similar activities that would cause them to be similarly impacted by economic or other conditions. At December&nbsp;31,
	2015, no significant concentrations, as defined above, existed in our portfolio in excess of 10% of total loans.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	- 47 -
</P>

	MANAGEMENT&#146;S DISCUSSION AND ANALYSIS
</B>

	&nbsp;

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
<B>
	Loans Held for Sale and Loan Servicing Rights.
</B>
	&nbsp;&nbsp;Loans held for sale (not
	included in the loan portfolio composition table) were entirely comprised of residential real estate mortgages and totaled $1.4 million and $755 thousand as of December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	We sell certain qualifying newly originated or refinanced residential real estate mortgages on the secondary market.&nbsp;Residential real
	estate mortgages serviced for others, which are not included in the consolidated statements of financial condition, amounted to $196.0 million and $215.2 million as of December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, respectively.
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:14PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The following table sets forth the allocation of the allowance for loan losses by loan category as of the
	dates indicated.&nbsp;The allocation is made for analytical purposes and is not necessarily indicative of the categories in which actual losses may occur.&nbsp;The total allowance is available to absorb losses from any segment of the loan portfolio
	(in thousands).
</P>

<A HREF="#D120623D10K_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
<B>
	MANAGEMENT&#146;S DISCUSSION AND ANALYSIS
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Management believes that the allowance for loan losses at December&nbsp;31, 2015 is adequate
	to cover probable losses in the loan portfolio at that date. Factors beyond our control, however, such as general national and local economic conditions, can adversely impact the adequacy of the allowance for loan losses. As a result, no assurance
	can be given that adverse economic conditions or other circumstances will not result in increased losses in the portfolio or that the allowance for loan losses will be sufficient to meet actual loan losses. See Part I, Item 1A &#147;Risk
	Factors&#148; for the risks impacting this estimate. Management presents a quarterly review of the adequacy of the allowance for loan losses to the Audit Committee of our Board of Directors based on the methodology that is described in further
	detail in Part I, Item I &#147;Business&#148; under the section titled &#147;Lending Activities&#148;. See also &#147;Critical Accounting Estimates&#148; for additional information on the allowance for loan losses.
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:14PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Non-performing assets include non-performing loans, foreclosed assets and non-performing investment
	securities.&nbsp;Non-performing assets at December&nbsp;31, 2015 were $8.6 million, a decrease of $1.7 million from the $10.3 million balance at December&nbsp;31, 2014.&nbsp;The primary component of non-performing assets is non-performing loans,
	which were $8.4 million or 0.41% of total loans at December&nbsp;31, 2015, a decrease of $1.7 million from $10.1 million or 0.53% of total loans at December&nbsp;31, 2014.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Approximately $2.0 million, or 24%, of the $8.4 million in non-performing loans as of December&nbsp;31, 2015 were current with respect to
	payment of principal and interest, but were classified as non-accruing because repayment in full of principal and/or interest was uncertain.&nbsp;The amount of interest income forgone totaled $432 thousand and $527 thousand for non-accruing loans
	outstanding as of December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, respectively.&nbsp;Included in nonaccrual loans are troubled debt restructurings (&#147;TDRs&#148;) of $2.4 million and $3.0 million at December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, respectively. We had no TDRs
	that were accruing interest as of December&nbsp;31, 2015 or 2014.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Foreclosed assets consist of real property formerly pledged as
	collateral for loans, which we have acquired through foreclosure proceedings or acceptance of a deed in lieu of foreclosure.&nbsp;Foreclosed asset holdings represented four properties totaling $163 thousand at December&nbsp;31, 2015 and four
	properties totaling $194 thousand at December&nbsp;31, 2014.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Potential problem loans are loans that are currently performing, but
	information known about possible credit problems of the borrowers causes us to have concern as to the ability of such borrowers to comply with the present loan payment terms and may result in disclosure of such loans as nonperforming at some time in
	the future.&nbsp;These loans remain in a performing status due to a variety of factors, including payment history, the value of collateral supporting the credits, and/or personal or government guarantees.&nbsp;We consider loans classified as
	substandard, which continue to accrue interest, to be potential problem loans.&nbsp;We identified $12.1 million and $13.7 million in loans that continued to accrue interest which were classified as substandard as of December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014,
	respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	- 49 -
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
<B>
	MANAGEMENT&#146;S DISCUSSION AND ANALYSIS
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	FUNDING ACTIVITIES
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Deposits
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The following table summarizes
	the composition of our deposits (dollars in thousands).
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	We offer a variety of deposit products designed to attract and retain customers, with the primary focus on
	building and expanding long-term relationships.&nbsp;At December&nbsp;31, 2015, total deposits were $2.73 billion, representing an increase of $280.0 million for the year. Time deposits were approximately 23% and 24% of total deposits at
	December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, respectively.&nbsp;Depositors remain hesitant to invest in time deposits, such as certificates of deposit, for long periods due to the low interest rate environment.&nbsp;This has resulted in lower amounts being
	placed in time deposits for generally shorter terms.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Nonpublic deposits, the largest component of our funding sources, totaled $2.05
	billion and $1.84 billion at December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, respectively, and represented 75% of total deposits as of the end of each period.&nbsp;We have managed this segment of funding through a strategy of competitive pricing that minimizes the
	number of customer relationships that have only a single service high cost deposit account.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	As an additional source of funding, we offer a
	variety of public (municipal) deposit products to the towns, villages, counties and school districts within our market.&nbsp;Public deposits generally range from 20% to 30% of our total deposits.&nbsp;There is a high degree of seasonality in this
	component of funding, because the level of deposits varies with the seasonal cash flows for these public customers.&nbsp;We maintain the necessary levels of short-term liquid assets to accommodate the seasonality associated with public
	deposits.&nbsp;Total public deposits were $675.7 million and $607.5 million at December 31, 2015 and December 31, 2014, respectively, and represented 25% of total deposits as of the end of each period.&nbsp;The increase in public deposits during
	2015 was due largely to successful business development efforts.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:8PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	We had no traditional brokered deposits at December&nbsp;31, 2015 or
	December&nbsp;31, 2014; however, we do participate in the CDARS and ICS programs, which enable depositors to receive FDIC insurance coverage for deposits otherwise exceeding the maximum insurable amount.&nbsp;CDARS and ICS deposits are considered
	brokered deposits for regulatory reporting purposes.&nbsp;Through these programs, deposits in excess of the maximum insurable amount are placed with multiple participating financial institutions.&nbsp;Reciprocal CDARS deposits and ICS deposits
	totaled $92.9 million and $146.6 million, respectively, at December&nbsp;31, 2015, compared to $79.7 million and $67.1 million, respectively, at December&nbsp;31, 2014.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	- 50 -
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<U>
	Short-term borrowings
</U>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Federal funds purchased are short-term borrowings that typically mature within one to ninety days.&nbsp;Short-term repurchase agreements are
	secured overnight borrowings with customers.&nbsp;We discontinued the customer repurchase agreement product during the second quarter of 2015 and transferred most of those customers into the ICS deposit product.&nbsp;Short-term FHLB borrowings have
	original maturities of less than one year and include overnight borrowings which we typically utilize to address short term funding needs as they arise.&nbsp;Short-term FHLB borrowings at December&nbsp;31, 2015 consisted of $116.8 million in
	overnight borrowings and $176.3 million in short-term advances.&nbsp;Short-term FHLB borrowings at December&nbsp;31, 2014 consisted of $129.0 million in overnight borrowings and $166.3 million in short-term advances.&nbsp;The FHLB borrowings are
	collateralized by securities from the Company&#146;s investment portfolio and certain qualifying loans. At December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, the Company&#146;s borrowings had a weighted average rate of 0.53% and 0.35%, respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	We have credit capacity with the FHLB and can borrow through facilities that include amortizing and term advances or repurchase agreements. We
	had approximately $76 million of immediate credit capacity with the FHLB as of December&nbsp;31, 2015. We had approximately $497 million in secured borrowing capacity at the Federal Reserve Bank (&#147;FRB&#148;) discount window, none of which was
	outstanding at December&nbsp;31, 2015. The FHLB and FRB credit capacity are collateralized by securities from our investment portfolio and certain qualifying loans. We had $120 million of credit available under unsecured federal funds purchased
	lines with various banks as of December&nbsp;31, 2015.&nbsp;Additionally, we had approximately $237 million of unencumbered liquid securities available for pledging.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The Parent has a revolving line of credit with a commercial bank allowing borrowings up to $20.0 million in total as an additional source of
	working capital.&nbsp;At December&nbsp;31, 2015, no amounts have been drawn on the line of credit.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:10PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The following table summarizes
	information relating to our short-term borrowings (dollars in thousands).
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:8PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:12PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<U>
	Long-term borrowings
</U>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	On April&nbsp;15, 2015, we issued $40.0 million of Subordinated Notes in a registered public offering.&nbsp;The Subordinated Notes bear
	interest at a fixed rate of 6.0% per year, payable semi-annually, for the first 10 years.&nbsp;From April&nbsp;15, 2025 to the April&nbsp;15, 2030 maturity date, the interest rate will reset quarterly to an annual interest rate equal to the then
	current three-month London Interbank Offered Rate (LIBOR) plus 3.944%, payable quarterly.&nbsp;The Subordinated Notes are redeemable by the us at any quarterly interest payment date beginning on April&nbsp;15, 2025 to maturity at par, plus accrued
	and unpaid interest.&nbsp;Proceeds, net of debt issuance costs of $1.1 million, were $38.9 million. The net proceeds from this offering were used for general corporate purposes, including but not limited to, contribution of capital to the Bank to
	support both organic growth and opportunistic acquisitions.&nbsp;The Subordinated Notes qualify as Tier 2 capital for regulatory purposes.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	- 51 -
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage52"></A>

<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<H5 ALIGN="LEFT">
<A HREF="#D120623D10K_HTM_TOC">
	Table of Contents
</A>
</H5>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
<B>
	MANAGEMENT&#146;S DISCUSSION AND ANALYSIS
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Shareholders&#146; Equity
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Total shareholders&#146; equity was $293.8 million at December&nbsp;31, 2015, an increase of $14.3 million from $279.5 million at
	December&nbsp;31, 2014. Net income for the year increased shareholders&#146; equity by $28.3 million, respectively, which were partially offset by common and preferred stock dividends declared of $12.7 million. Accumulated other comprehensive loss
	included in shareholders&#146; equity increased $2.3 million during the year due primarily to lower net unrealized gains on securities available for sale. The decrease of $1.3 million in treasury stock during 2015 was primarily due to the issuance
	of restricted stock awards with an aggregate grant date fair value of $1.1 million.&nbsp;For detailed information on shareholders&#146; equity, see Note 12, Shareholders&#146; Equity, of the notes to consolidated financial statements. FII and the
	Bank are subject to various regulatory capital requirements. At December&nbsp;31, 2015, both FII and the Bank exceeded all regulatory requirements. For detailed information on regulatory capital requirements, see Note 11, Regulatory Matters, of the
	notes to consolidated financial statements.
</P>
</EFX_RESULTS_OF_OPERATIONS>
<EFX_LIQUIDITY_CAPITAL>
<A NAME="FIS_LIQUIDITY_CAPITAL"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:26PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	LIQUIDITY AND CAPITAL RESOURCES
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The objective of maintaining adequate liquidity is to assure that we meet our financial obligations.&nbsp;These obligations include the
	withdrawal of deposits on demand or at their contractual maturity, the repayment of matured borrowings, the ability to fund new and existing loan commitments and the ability to take advantage of new business opportunities.&nbsp;We achieve liquidity
	by maintaining a strong base of core customer funds, maturing short-term assets, our ability to sell or pledge securities, lines-of-credit, and access to the financial and capital markets.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Liquidity for the Bank is managed through the monitoring of anticipated changes in loans, the investment portfolio, core deposits and wholesale
	funds. The strength of the Bank&#146;s liquidity position is a result of its base of core customer deposits. These core deposits are supplemented by wholesale funding sources that include credit lines with the other banking institutions, the FHLB
	and the FRB.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The primary sources of liquidity for FII are dividends from the Bank and access to financial and capital
	markets.&nbsp;Dividends from the Bank are limited by various regulatory requirements related to capital adequacy and earnings trends.&nbsp;The Bank relies on cash flows from operations, core deposits, borrowings and short-term liquid assets.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	Cash and cash equivalents were $60.1 million as of December&nbsp;31, 2015, an increase of $1.9 million from $58.2 million as of
	December&nbsp;31, 2014.&nbsp;Net cash provided by operating activities totaled $43.1 million and the principal source of operating activity cash flow was net income adjusted for noncash income and expense items.&nbsp;Net cash used in investing
	activities totaled $305.9 million, which included outflows of $180.1 million for net loan originations and $118.6 million from net investment securities transactions.&nbsp;Net cash provided by financing activities of $264.8 million was attributed to
	a $280.0 million increase in deposits and net proceeds of $38.9 million from the Subordinated Notes issuance, partly offset by $12.7 million in dividend payments and a $41.7 million decrease in short-term borrowings.
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
<B>
	MANAGEMENT&#146;S DISCUSSION AND ANALYSIS
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Off-Balance Sheet Arrangements
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	With the exception of obligations in connection with our irrevocable loan commitments, operating leases and limited partnership investments as
	of December&nbsp;31, 2015, we had no other off-balance sheet arrangements that have or are reasonably likely to have a current or future effect on our financial condition, changes in financial condition, revenues or expenses, results of operations,
	liquidity, capital expenditures or capital resources that is material to investors.&nbsp;For additional information on off-balance sheet arrangements, see Note 1, Summary of Significant Accounting Policies and Note 10, Commitments and Contingencies,
	in the notes to the accompanying consolidated financial statements.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:20PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Security Yields and Maturities Schedule
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The following table sets forth certain information regarding the amortized cost (&#147;Cost&#148;), weighted average yields (&#147;Yield&#148;)
	and contractual maturities of our debt securities portfolio as of December&nbsp;31, 2015. Mortgage-backed securities are included in maturity categories based on their stated maturity date. Actual maturities may differ from the contractual
	maturities presented because borrowers may have the right to call or prepay certain investments. No tax-equivalent adjustments were made to the weighted average yields (dollars in thousands).
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:16PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Contractual Loan Maturity Schedule

</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">

	origination costs, include principal amortization and non-accruing loans.&nbsp;Demand loans having no stated schedule of repayment or maturity and overdrafts are reported as due in one year or less (in thousands).

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
<B>
	MANAGEMENT&#146;S DISCUSSION AND ANALYSIS
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Capital Resources
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The FRB has adopted a system using risk-based capital guidelines to evaluate the capital adequacy of bank holding companies on a consolidated
	basis.&nbsp;The final rules implementing the Basel Committee on Banking Supervision&#146;s (&#147;BCBS&#148;) capital guidelines for U.S. banks became effective for the Company on January&nbsp;1, 2015, with full compliance with all of the final
	requirements phased in over a multi-year schedule, to be fully phased-in by January&nbsp;1, 2019. As of December&nbsp;31, 2015, the Company&#146;s capital levels remained characterized as &#147;well-capitalized&#148; under the new rules. We continue
	to evaluate the potential impact that regulatory rules may have on our liquidity and capital management strategies, including Basel III and those required under the Dodd-Frank Act. See Note 11, Regulatory Matters of the notes to consolidated
	financial statements and the &#147;Basel III Capital Rules&#148; section below for further discussion. The following table reflects the Company&#146;s ratios and their components as of December&nbsp;31 (in thousands):
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:6PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:14PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN">
<B>
	Basel III Capital Rules
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	In July&nbsp;2013, the FRB and the FDIC approved the final rules implementing the BCBS&#146;s capital guidelines for U.S. banks. Under the
	final rules, minimum requirements will increase for both the quantity and quality of capital held by the Company. The rules include a new common equity Tier 1 capital to risk-weighted assets minimum ratio of 4.5%, raise the minimum ratio of Tier 1
	capital to risk-weighted assets from 4.0% to 6.0%, require a minimum ratio of total capital to risk-weighted assets of 8.0%, and require a minimum Tier 1 leverage ratio of 4.0%. A new capital conservation buffer is also established above the
	regulatory minimum capital requirements. This capital conservation buffer will be phased in beginning January&nbsp;1, 2016 at 0.625% of risk-weighted assets and will increase each subsequent year by an additional 0.625% until reaching its final
	level of 2.5% on January&nbsp;1, 2019. Strict eligibility criteria for regulatory capital instruments were also implemented under the final rules. The final rules also revise the definition and calculation of Tier 1 capital, total capital, and
	risk-weighted assets.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:6PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="JUSTIFY">
	The phase-in period for the final rules became effective for the Company on January&nbsp;1, 2015, with full
	compliance with all of the final rules&#146; requirements phased in over a multi-year schedule, to be fully phased-in by January&nbsp;1, 2019. As of December&nbsp;31, 2015, the Company&#146;s capital levels remained characterized as
	&#147;well-capitalized&#148; under the new rules.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT ; FONT-SIZE:8PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:0PT; MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT; FONT-SIZE:10PT; FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN" ALIGN="CENTER">
	- 54 -
</P>
